stershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Murdac","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Irish, Scottish:  see  Murdoch  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Murdoch","meanings":["Scottish: from an Anglicized form of the Gaelic personal names <i>Muireadhach</i> ‘mariner’, <i>Murchadh</i> ‘sea-warrior’, and <i>Muircheartach</i> ‘sea-ruler’, the first element in each being <i>muir</i> ‘sea’. The personal name was introduced into Yorkshire and Normandy by Norsemen from Ireland as early as the 10th century. The surname in post-Conquest medieval England usually belongs to Norman families."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Murdac was born about 1310, in Europe, his father, Henry Murdac, was 11308 and his mother, Coheiress of Gilbert Pigot, was 27. He had at least 1 daughter with Isolda of Leicestershire."},"et":{"about 1310–":"umbes 1310–Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1244–1267":"1244–1267","1343–1383":"1343–1383","1268–Male":"1268–Surnud","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","before 1310":"enne 1310","1268":"1268","1267":"1267","1343":"1343","1244":"1244","1310":"1310","1285":"1285","about 1310":"umbes 1310","1383":"1383","Europe":